title: Spallation-Fission Competition in Astatine Compound Nuclei Formed by Heavy-Ion Bombardment

x4freetext: Spallation-Fission Competition in Astatine Compound
Nuclei Formed by Heavy-Ion Bombardment

x4freetext: The heavy ion linear accelerator
(HILAC).
As no At211 was produced in the Hilac
bombardments, it was possible to determine chemical
yields by using At211 as a tracer. Following the
heavy-ion bombardment, the recoil catcher containing
the heavy-ion-produced activities and a plate
containing a known amount of tracer activity were
simultaneously dissolved in 8M HCl. The astatine was
separated from other alpha-emitting activities
(mainly polonium) by extraction into di-isopropyl
ether (DIPE) . The DIPE fraction was transferred to a
platinum counting disk and evaporated to dryness
under a heat lamp. The only absolute counting was
that of the plates containing At211 tracer. The alpha
particles from At211 (and EC daughter, Po211) were
counted in an ionization chamber having 50% geometry.
In "ratio experiments", stacked foils (consisting of
gold targets and aluminum foils) were bombarded and
the ratios of production of low-activity astatine
nuclides to that of the prominent activities were
measured. For measurements of Pt(N14,xn) cross
sections, in addition to other types of experiments,
it was necessary to do ratio experiments.
Cross sections were calculated in the usual manner,
using the branching ratios and half-lives listed.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: The limits of error given for these cross
sections represent estimated uncertainties in the
positions of the smoothed curves. These estimates, as
well as the limits of error given for the other cross
sections, include uncertainties in the counting rates
of the radiations from the product nuclei, target
thickness, and decay during bombardment corrections.
Uncertainty in the values used for the alpha/EC
branching ratios have not been included.

Thin uniform targets were made by vaporizing <= 100
microg/cm2 of gold  metal onto a known
area of previously weighed 0.25-mi1. Al foils. Target
thicknesses were determined by weighing the foils
before and after vaporization.  Targets
for the "ratio experiments" were of gold leaf (approx
2 mg/cm2). Pieces of gold leaf, backed by 0.25-mil
Al foils, were stacked in the assembly.
Fig. 1, page 1807.

x4freetext: Thin uniform targets were made by vaporizing <= 100
microg/cm2 of  platinum metal onto a known
area of previously weighed 0.25-mi1. Al foils. Target
thicknesses were determined by weighing the foils
before and after vaporization. Targets for the
"ratio experiments" were made by electroplating 200
to 300 microg/cm2 of metallic platinum onto 0.1-mil
Ag foil. Targets of natural platinum and platinum
were used. Target thicknesses were determined by
weighing the foils before and after plating.
Fig. 2, page 1808.
